p: The expression of several cellular genes is purported to be influence by the RSV G glycoprotein (for comprehensive review see Oshansky, et al [ 25]), including several TLRs, interferon and STAT-related genes. Functional fingerprint analyses of the expression of these genes during viral infection are presented in Fig 6C. Again, the viruses appear to segregate in a similar fashion based on the expression of these genes. Thus, NH1161B, NH1001B and NH1125B, inducing higher levels of expression of these genes as compared with the low inducers subgroup B strains. Among the genes up-regulated by the “high inducers” are several key components of antiviral pathways including STAT1, STAT2, MYD88, MAVS, TLRs among others.
